Section A: Visualization of the Data¶

Task:¶

Read the data and visualize one instance (all axes) from each class and try to relate the shape (time series) you see with the gestures shown in Figure 1. A 3D scatter plot would be interesting. Note that this is an acceleration information. You can transform this information to a velocity vector by computing the cumulative sum of acceleration over time.

Acceleration to Position¶

First of all, I cumulated the data two times over the time series to transform acceloration data to position data.

In [27]:

c_dfy = dfy.iloc[:, 1:316].cumsum(axis=1).cumsum(axis=1)

c_dfx_class = pd.concat([dfx.iloc[:, 0:1], c_dfx.iloc[:, 0:315]], axis = 1, sort=False)
c_dfx_class['Time Series ID'] = range(1, len(c_dfx_class) + 1)
melt_dfx = pd.melt(c_dfx_class, id_vars=[dfx.columns[0],dfx.columns[316]], var_name='Time Series', value_name='X')
melt_dfy = pd.melt(c_dfy, var_name='Time Series', value_name='Y')
melt_dfz = pd.melt(c_dfz, var_name='Time Series', value_name='Z')

melt_df = pd.concat([melt_dfx, melt_dfy.iloc[:, 1:2], melt_dfz.iloc[:, 1:2]], axis = 1, sort=False)

cols = list(melt_df.columns.values)
melt_df = melt_df[cols [1:6] + [cols[0]]]
melt_df = melt_df.sort_values(['Time Series ID','Time Series'])

Visualization of Data: 3D Scatter Plot¶

In [21]:
cols_dfx = list(dfx.columns.values)
cl_tseries = dfx[[cols_dfx[0]] + [cols_dfx[316]]]

a = [1,2,3,4,5,6,7,8]

for i in a:
    cl_tseries_flt = cl_tseries.loc[(cl_tseries[0] == i)]
    b = rd.randint(0,cl_tseries_flt.shape[0]-1)
    
    new_df = melt_df.loc[(melt_df['Class'] == i) & (melt_df['Time Series ID']== cl_tseries_flt.iloc[b,1])]
    
    fig = pyplot.figure()
    ax = Axes3D(fig)
    ax.scatter(new_df["X"], new_df["Y"], new_df["Z"], label = b)
    ax.set_title("Class {}".format(i))
    plt.legend()
    pyplot.show()

With the help of the for loop, I plotted random time series for a couple of times. With the usage of position data, the obtained shapes seems quite similar to gestures in Figure 1.

As it can be seen in shapes are almost the same of the gestures.

For example, position datas of shape 1 and 2 are exactly the same.

Section B: Application of PCA¶

Task:¶

Suppose our aim is to reduce this multivariate time series to a univariate one with a dimensionality reduction approach. Suppose we decide to reduce the data from 3D (i.e. X, Y and Z features) to 1D using PCA. Relevant columns for PCA is X, Y and Z. Apply PCA to the whole data (regardless of the time series id or class) and report PCA results.

Select 2 random time series from each class and visualize the reduced dimensions as time series in a single plot to see if classes can be separated in the reduced dimensions.

Visualization¶

In [30]:
for i in a:
    cl_tseries_flt = cl_tseries.loc[(cl_tseries[0] == i)]
    b = rd.randint(0,cl_tseries_flt.shape[0]-1)
    c = rd.randint(0,cl_tseries_flt.shape[0]-1)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(9,5))

    new1D_1_df = melt1D_df.loc[(melt_df['Class'] == i) & (melt1D_df['Time Series ID']== cl_tseries_flt.iloc[b,1])]
    new1D_2_df = melt1D_df.loc[(melt_df['Class'] == i) & (melt1D_df['Time Series ID']== cl_tseries_flt.iloc[c,1])]
    plt.scatter(new1D_1_df["Time Series"], new1D_1_df["1D"], s = 10, label = b)
    plt.scatter(new1D_1_df["Time Series"], new1D_2_df["1D"], s = 10, label = c)
    
    plt.xticks()
    plt.ylabel('1D')
    plt.xlabel('Time Series')
    plt.title("Class {}".format(i))
    loc='upper right'
    bbox_to_anchor=(0.5, 0.5)
    plt.legend()
    plt.show()

After plotting the 1D datas of two different random time series from each class, It seems like each class draw similar paths.

Both of the instances in class 1 follow similar paths. There are also similar results in class 6 so it might be a little bit harder to separate class 1 and class 6. However, class 6 seems to be ended smoothly compared to class 1. In the figure 1, both class 1 and class 6 gestures go down and this may explain the similarities between them.

In class 2, instances follows a specific path which can be easily separated by others. It started with a concave shape and then turned into convex. It can be easily differentiated from other classes.

Instances in class 3 and class 4 seems to be vice versa. It is logical because class 3 gesture is a move that goes left-to-right and class 4 gesture is a move that goes right-to-left. It is possible to spereate them by visual inspection.

Instances in class 5 and class 6 are also vice versa with the similar reason of class 3 and 4. It is possible to seperate them from other classes by visual inspection.

Class 7 and class 8 seems similar with slight differences. Small pit at the beginning of class 8 may provide some vision for classification.

As a result, mostly, it seems possible to classify instances and separate classes with visualization of the 1D data.

With the visualization of the data, classes seems to be focused on different location on the plot. Especially, class 5, 6 and 4 are seperable.

I also would like to see if vice versa gestures have similar or different results.

Reduced datas in class 3 are mostly on right hand side of 0 value and upper side of value 0 in dimension 1 and 2, respectively. Reduced datas in class 4 seems to be opposite of class 3. It may be concluded by the effect of direction of the movement.
